## What happened

.NET 11 removed the OpenSSL-based DSA shim on macOS. Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have **never** supported DSA, so previously .NET shipped an OpenSSL interop layer for it on macOS. As part of the ongoing DSA deprecation (the algorithm has been obsolete since `SYSLIB0030`), .NET 11 drops that shim — `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and iOS/tvOS).

Windows and Linux are unaffected because Windows CNG and OpenSSL on Linux still expose DSA.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), the cleanest cross-platform fix is to use **BouncyCastle**, which has a fully managed DSA implementation:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-dependent code:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 10) — breaks on macOS under .NET 11
using System.Security.Cryptography;

bool Verify(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DSAParameters keyParams)
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();       // throws on macOS/.NET 11
    dsa.ImportParameters(keyParams);
    return dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
}

// After — works everywhere via managed code
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Math;

bool Verify(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DSAParameters keyParams)
{
    var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(
        new BigInteger(1, keyParams.Y),
        new DsaParameters(
            new BigInteger(1, keyParams.P),
            new BigInteger(1, keyParams.Q),
            new BigInteger(1, keyParams.G)));

    var signer = new DsaSigner();
    signer.Init(false, pubKey);

    // Decode the DER-encoded (r, s) signature
    var seq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)
        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);
    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)seq[0]).Value;
    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)seq[1]).Value;

    byte[] hash;
    using (var sha1 = System.Security.Cryptography.SHA1.Create())
        hash = sha1.ComputeHash(data);

    return signer.VerifySignature(hash, r, s);
}
```

**Key points:**
- BouncyCastle's DSA is pure managed C# — no platform dependencies.
- Long-term, plan to migrate away from DSA entirely (ECDSA or Ed25519).
- If you only target Windows + Linux, you could also gate with `RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform()` and keep the built-in API, but BouncyCastle is simpler for uniform cross-platform support.
